{"key":"processedPost-9714678","value":{"id":9714678,"first":9712007,"last":9715181,"when":1233465531,"utime":"02/01/09 07:18 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /> I guess what I'm wondering is, how do you distinguish two adjacent sectors that are both rhizo?<br /></blockquote><br /><br />They will be distinct 'fans' radiating out from the center like spokes on a wheel.&nbsp; You'll be able to tell them apart.&nbsp; As for your dish, you can have cottony and rhizo mycelium from the same isolate.<br /><br />To verify, take tiny pieces of rhizo mycelium from different areas that are separated by cottony mycelium, and put them 1 inch apart from each other on the same dish.&nbsp; If they grow seamlessly together, they were the same isolate.&nbsp; If they form a line of isolation or separation between them, then they were indeed two sectors, thus different strains.<br />RR","title":"Re: strain isolation from grain transfer","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}